[[Image:Humidcontinentalworld2.png|thumb|250px|''[[Humid continental climate]]'' worldwide]] {{climate chart |[[Moscow]] |-9|-4|46 |-10|-3|36 |-4|3|33 |3|11|38 |8|19|52 |12|22|84 |15|24|90 |13|22|80 |8|16|67 |3|9|66 |-3|1|60 |-7|-3|53 |source= |float=right |clear=right |units=metric }} [[Moscow]] has a [[humid continental climate]] ([[Köppen climate classification]] ''Dfb'') with warm, sometimes hot, somewhat humid summers and long, cold winters. Typical high temperatures in the warm months of June, July and August are around {{convert|23|°C|°F|abbr=on|lk=on}}, but during heat waves, which can occur anytime from May to September, daytime temperature highs often top {{convert|30|°C|°F|abbr=on}} for sometimes one or two weeks. In the winter, temperatures normally drop to approximately {{convert|-10|°C|°F|abbr=on}}, though there can be periods of warmth with temperatures rising above {{convert|0|°C}}. Summer lasts from mid-May to the beginning of September. Winter lasts from the beginning of November to the end of March.
== Monthly averages and records for Moscow == [[File:VVC weather station.png|thumb|200px|left|Location of the [[VVC weather station]] on the map of Moscow]] The highest temperature ever recorded was {{Convert|38.2|°C|°F|abbr=on}} on July 29, 2010, and minimum temperature recorded was {{convert|-42|°C|°F}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Moscow, Russia|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=551572&cityname=Moscow-Central-Federal-District-Russia|publisher=Weatherbase}}</ref> In 2007 three record highs for the month occurred – January + {{convert|8.6|°C|°F}}, March + {{convert|17.5|°C|°F}}, and May + {{convert|33.2|°C|°F}}; in 2008, there were new record highs for December and the entire winter: + {{convert|9.6|°C|°F}}. On July 23, 2010, the temperature reached {{Convert|36.7|°C|°F|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.ruvr.ru/2010/07/24/13327739.html |title=Air temperatures in Moscow beat all records |accessdate=2010-07-24}}</ref> and continued to set record highs each following day until it finally reached + {{convert|38.2|°C|°F}} on July 29, 2010. In November 2010 a new month record high of +{{convert|14.5|°C|°F}} occurred (after +12.6 in 1927). [[File:Moscow region temp.PNG|thumb|250px|right|Maximum temperature in Moscow and near regions during [[2010 Northern Hemisphere summer heat wave]]]]
Average annual temperature in Moscow is {{Convert|5.8|°C|°F|abbr=on}}, but recently (2007, 2008, 2015) it has been higher than {{Convert|7|°C|°F|abbr=on}}.<ref name="pogoda (data) 1">{{cite web |url=http://www.pogoda.ru.net/data/27612.zip|title=Pogoda.ru.net (data), see article "Средняя (average)" |accessdate=January 8, 2009 |publisher= |language=Russian}}</ref> In the first half of the 20th century, there was light night frost in late summer.<ref name="pogoda (data) 2">{{cite web |url=http://www.pogoda.ru.net/data/27612.zip|title=Pogoda.ru.net (data), see article "Минимум (minimum)" |accessdate=January 8, 2009 |publisher= |language=Russian}}</ref>
Monthly rainfall totals vary minimally throughout the year, although the [[Precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]] levels tend to be higher during the summer than during the winter. Due to the significant variation in temperature between the winter and summer months as well as the limited fluctuation in precipitation levels during the summer, Moscow is considered to be within a [[continental climate]] zone.
Most of records and averages are given for [[VVC weather station]], located in the [[Administrative divisions of Moscow|North-Eastern administrative okrug]] of Moscow. The temperature from this station averages 0.5–1&nbsp;°C lower than in the city center, and 0.5–2&nbsp;°C higher than night minimums in the suburbs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hmn.ru:8101/index1.php?code=22|title=Data from weather stations of Moscow region in real time |accessdate=March 25, 2009 |publisher= |language=Russian}}</ref> <!---IMPORTANT NOTE: Moscow is large and naturally has different records at different points. Records for All-Russia Exhibition Centre|VVC (VDNKh) weather station)--->
